# Split the dataset by year and check the seasonal pattern in each year.
year_list=df_sub.index.year.unique()
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,12))
for year in year_list:
    data=df_sub[df_sub.index.year==year]
    ax.plot(data.index.month,data["CPI_electricity"],label=year);
handles,labels=ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
ax.legend(reversed(handles),reversed(labels),bbox_to_anchor=(1,1),ncol=1);
loc=df_sub.index.month.unique().sort_values()
plt.xticks(loc,loc);
plt.xlabel("Month");
plt.ylabel("Index");
plt.title("CPI for Electricity in Each Year");

We can see there was always a peak in months June to September. In my guess, it's summertime between June and September, so the higher electricity consumption might because of the more usage of airconditioner. And the CPI for electricity is also a slightly higher in November and December, I guess this is because of the more heating needs during winter time.

1. Exponantial Smoothing Model¶


We can see the residuals are more volatile in the early and later years, a roughly increasing error in recent years as compared with years between 1985 and 2001. There's also an upward approximately linear trend and a constant seasonal component as well. Therefore, I'm going to use the Holt-Winter's Seasonal Smoothing Model. One model doesn't have damping factor, the second one has damping factor.

2. Seasonal ARIMA Model¶


As we discovered a constant seasonal pattern above, I need to make the time series stationary.

Taking a first difference of seasonal difference.

In [46]:
test_stationarity(df_sub["seasonal_first_difference"].dropna(inplace=False))

Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:
Test Statistic                -9.758365e+00
p-value                        7.680559e-17
#Lags Used                     1.100000e+01
Number of Observations Used    4.910000e+02
Critical Value (1%)           -3.443739e+00
Critical Value (5%)           -2.867444e+00
Critical Value (10%)          -2.569915e+00
dtype: float64

The p-value Dickey-Fuller test of seasonal_first_difference series is very close to zero. This series is stationary now.

  • Plot the ACF and PACF and find the optimal parameters for the model.

ACF and PACF of seasonal_first_difference series

In [52]:
# seasonal_first_difference
fig=plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))
ax1=fig.add_subplot(211)
fig=sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf(df_sub["seasonal_first_difference"].dropna(inplace=False),lags=50,ax=ax1)
ax2=fig.add_subplot(212)
fig=sm.graphics.tsa.plot_pacf(df_sub["seasonal_first_difference"].dropna(inplace=False),lags=50,ax=ax2)

D and d parameters should all be 1, the positive lag 1 in both autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plot also confirmed that p should be 1, and there's a significant lag at the first season at 12 in both acf and pacf plots, so Q is 1 as well. So the ARIMA model should be ARIMA(1,1,0)x(0,1,1,12).

From the above plots, we can see the ETS model with damping has fewer strong autocorrelations in ACF and partial autocorrelation in PACF. ETS model is better.

  • Information Criteria
    From the above result summary of each model, we've already known the AIC and BIC.

ic=pd.DataFrame(data={"AIC":[296.447,281.846,1685.186],"BIC":[361.467,350.931,1697.847]},index=[["ETS without dampen","ETS with dampen","ARIMA"]])

                         AIC       BIC
ETS without dampen   296.447   361.467
ETS with dampen      281.846   350.931

The information Criteria shows that ETS with dampen has the lowest AIC, which would be the best model.

From the table above, we can see the ARIMA model has the highest accuracy. ARIMA is better than ETS without dampen and ETS without dampen is better than ETS with dampen. But considering both the goodness of fit of the model and the complexity, I decide to choose ETS with dampen model.
